entral bud forms the tail and body of the pancreas","The dorsal bud rotates around the duodenum","The ventral bud forms most of the pancreatic tissue"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ventral bud rotates around the duodenum and combines with the dorsal bud. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eventral bud forms the uncinate process and part of the head\u003C/strong\u003E of the pancreas, whereas the dorsal bud forms the head, body, and tail.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal and ventral buds arise from the midgut\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as they originate from the foregut endoderm. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eventral bud forms the tail and body\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as these structures are formed by the dorsal bud. The \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal bud rotates around the duodenum\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it is the ventral bud that rotates. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eventral bud forms most of the pancreatic tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the dorsal bud forms the majority of the pancreas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The pancreas develops from dorsal and ventral buds of the foregut endoderm.","The ventral pancreatic bud rotates around the duodenum and fuses with the dorsal bud.","The ventral bud forms the uncinate process and part of the pancreatic head."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Ehrhardt JD, Gomez F. Embryology, Pancreas. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545243/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96683"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15924"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96683"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T15:06:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T15:20:40+